The Kano State Governor, Dr Umar Abdullahi Ganduje on Tuesday rejected the voluntary resignations of his Chief of Staff, Ali Haruna Makoda, Commissioners of Budget and Planning, Nura Dankadai, Education, Saidu Kiru and Health, Aminu Ibrahim Tsanyawa. The development came on the heels of official acceptance of eight Commissioners that have dropped their jobs at the expiration of a Monday deadline by the Governor to his appointees seeking political positions to resign, according to section 84(2) of the 2021 Electoral Law. A statement by Abba Anwar, Chief press Secretary to Ganduje, quoted his principal to have accepted the resignation of his Deputy Governor, Dr Nasir Yusuf Gawuna as the Honourable Commissioner for Agriculture & Natural Resources, Murtala Sule Garo as the Honourable Commissioner for Local Govt and Chieftancy Affairs, Ibrahim Abubakar Karaye as the Honourable Commissioner for Culture and Tourism Others whose Resignations were accepted includes, Mahmud Muhammad Santsi as the Honourable Commissioner for Housing & Transport, Muntari Ishaq Yakasai as the Honourable Commissioner for Special Duties The Governor also approved the Resignations of Musa Ilyasu Kwankwaso as the Honourable Commissioner for Rural & Community Development, Kabiru Ado Lakwaya as the Honourable Commissioner for Youth & Sports The Governor thanks them for their tremendous contributions to the development of the state and wishes them well in all future endeavours. According to him, concerning their resignation, the Permanent Secretaries of the affected ministries should take charge immediately. The Statement clearly explained that the Chief of Staff and all other Commissioners are directed to continue carrying out their duties in their respective ministries.